JavaScript Set Logic:

- Set Logic is an ECMAScript 2025 feature.
    union()
    difference()
    intersection()
    isDisjointFrom()
    isSubsetOf()
    isSupersetOf()
    symmetricDifference()


#) The union() Method:
    - The union() method returns the union of two sets.
    - The union() method returns a new set containing the elements which are in this set, or in the
        argument set, or in both:

        const A = new Set(['a','b','c']);
        const B = new Set(['b','c','d']);

        const C = A.union(B);

        let text1 = "";
        for(const x of C) {
            text1 += x;
        }
        document.getElementById("1").innerHTML = `Union of A and B: ${text1}`;  // abcd


#) The intersection() Method:
    - The intersection() method returns the intersection of two sets.
    - The intersection() method returns a new set containing the elements which are in this set and
        in the argument set:

        const A = new Set(['a','b','c']);
        const B = new Set(['b','c','d']);

        const D = A.intersection(B);

        let text2 = "";
        for(const x of D) {
            text2 += x;
        }
        document.getElementById("2").innerHTML = `Intersection of A and B: ${text2}`;  // bc


#) The difference() Method:
    - The difference() method returns the difference between two sets.
    - The difference() method returns a new set containing elements which are in this set but not in
        the argument set:
        
        const A = new Set(['a','b','c']);
        const B = new Set(['b','c','d']);

        const E = A.difference(B);

        let text3 = "";
        for(const x of E) {
            text3 += x;
        }
        document.getElementById("3").innerHTML = `Difference of A and B: ${text3}`;  // a


#) The symmetricDifference() Method:
    - The symmetricDifference() method returns the symmetric difference between to sets.
        (see symmetricDifference()_visually.png)
    - The symmetricDifference() method returns a new set containing elements which are in this set or
        in the argument set, but not in both:

        const A = new Set(['a','b','c']);
        const B = new Set(['b','c','d']);

        const F = A.symmetricDifference(B);

        let text4 = "";
        for(const x of F) {
            text4 += x;
        }
        document.getElementById("4").innerHTML = `symmetricDifference of A and B: ${text4}`;    // ad


#) The isSubsetOf() Method:
    - The isSubsetOf() method returns true if all elements in this set is also elements in the
        argument set:

        const A = new Set(['a','b','c']);
        const B = new Set(['b','c','d']);

        const answer = A.isSubsetOf(B);
        document.getElementById("5").innerHTML = `A isSubsetOf(B): ${answer}`;  // false


#) The isSupersetOf() Method:
    - The isSupersetOf() method returns true if all elements in the argument set are also in this
        set:

        const A = new Set(['a','b','c']);
        const B = new Set(['b','c','d']);

        const answer1 = A.isSupersetOf(B);
        document.getElementById("6").innerHTML = `A isSubsetOf(B): ${answer1}`;  // false


#) The isDisjointFrom() Method:
    - The isDisjointFrom() method returns true if this set has no elements in common with the
        argument set:

        const A = new Set(['a','b','c']);
        const B = new Set(['b','c','d']);

        const answer2 = A.isDisjointFrom(B);
        document.getElementById("7").innerHTML = `A isDisjointFrom(B): ${answer2}`;  // false